column5: Ἀλεξανδρος is a shop owner and good friend of Simon's household. His shop is in the agora.
Μαρία is the mother of the house, wife of Simon, a devout Hellenistic Jewish woman who has recently begun attending the meetings of "the way" in the house of Philip.
Διοδωρος is the teacher who holds classes each morning in the stoa.
Γεωργιος is the second child of Σίμων and Μαρία. He is a lively, energetic boy who doesn't always apply himself the way he should to his lessons.
Ἰασων is a slave belonging to Σίμων and Μαρία. He serves as the παιδαγώγος for Γεωργιος, trying to keep him out of trouble. As a result his patience is worn very thin and he has a sharp temper.
Νηρευς is a teacher, the tutor for Γεωργιος and a handful of other boys. He is a freedman and a bachelor. He holds his classes in the stoa at the city centre.
Σοφία is the daughter of Σιμών and Μαρία. She is their eldest child, but not yet of marriageable age.
Στεφανος is an elder in the Jewish synagogue and a teacher in the small Christian community.
Σίμων is the head of the household and your owner. He is the husband of Μαρία and an elder in the local synagogue.
Φοιβη is a house slave belonging to Simon and Maria.

Hi Peter. Actually υ doesn't make the "uh" sound in "cup" (really a shewa sound--a short grunt.) It's always a long (fairly nazal) "u" as in "tuna". So a vowel like ο or α would be closer to the "uh" in "cup" (κοπ or καπ), although technically that would sound more like "cop."
Thanks Karen. This one should now be fixed.
Thanks Kent. There was a bug with this step that I've fixed, though I've also removed βαλλ as a valid answer. In Greek you would only use a single λ to make the same sound as English 'll'.

column2: A few more updates have come out in the last few days. This news/updates system is finally up and running, so that I can keep you posted of any problems or changes. I've also fixed problems in the evaluation of several questions. Actually, in the process I over-wrote the database and lost a few newly added questions, so I'll be working to get those (and more new ones) added soon. Finally, you've probably noticed that the questions are now being asked by a person! This is the first step toward a more interesting, story-driven context for the questions. It won't be developed much until next year, but you can keep an eye out for more content like that.
column3: News system, fixed questions, and a new face

column2: This past week it slipped my mind to actually post the link to week 5's "path" until Wednesday. If that happens again (knowing how scattered I've been), just keep using the last-posted "path" until the new one shows up. Some of you took the initiative to do that, so kudos to you.
Fixed a couple more questions this morning from your bug reports.

I improved the error-handling behind the scenes today. You may not notice any difference . . . but that's the idea! In some situations where you used to get an error message after submitting your answer to a question, you will now get a nice message from the smiling woman and be able to continue gracefully. If you never find her apologizing for getting confused, it just means that the program is running smoothly. But this should lessen the anxiety created for students by error messages that break the flow of the "path".
Just added some new questions and fixed two bugs in questions. Thanks for the bug reports.

The Paideia site will be down briefly this evening between 10pm and about 10:20pm for maintenance. This will allow me to upgrade and fix sections of the site without causing errors if someone is using it at the same time. I hope this will not cause any inconvenience.

Well, it's 10:09pm on Monday and the Paideia site is finally working again. >whew<! The immediate change you'll notice is the "How am I doing?" section on your profile page. Whenever you want to see how your learning is progressing, just check there. 

Since the site was down all day today, you will only be required to log on four days this week. Happy learning!
Yes, we're still just in week 7 of the course, so the "path" for this week is 7. I just posted week 8 early so that I wouldn't forget!
More questions added today. I've discovered a way to filter out a lot of the errors when I'm creating them, so these should (!) be clean.

If you check your profile page today you'll find a new calendar listing the number of questions you attempted each day. Again, I've only been able to capture these stats beginning last Tuesday, but from here on they'll be available whenever you want to check. I don't yet have day labels on the calendars, so be aware that they are laid out Monday-Sunday (not Sunday-Saturday).

I also fixed errors on another two questions. Thanks for the bug reports!
column3: New Date Info on Your Profile Page

column2:
Thanks for the bug reports. I was able to fix the recent questions about καθως and γραψαι and to tweak the recent multiple-choice questions.

My next task will be to set up a system for giving you direct feedback when you submit a bug report and integrating those into your statistics. In the meantime, I do read them!

I've become aware, through a few of your emails, that there's a time-zone problem with the Paideia tracking of questions attempted each day. Depending on when you attempt questions during a day, they may end up being recorded as if you attempted them the following day. I'm looking into this, and will try to fix it. Rest assured, though, that it won't affect my grading at the end of term.

I'm going to be uploading some updated files to the server this afternoon after 3:40pm. It's best if you don't try to use the system while I'm updating, since your exercises won't be recorded. I'll post another message here as soon as the upgrades are finished. Sorry for any inconvenience!

OK, the upgrades are done for the moment. You'll now notice on your profile page (at the bottom) a list of the bug reports you've submitted. I will use this list to give you feedback on these reports, letting you know whether I think it's a bug and (if not) explaining why. So after you submit your next bug report check back there.
column3: Upgrades done and new profile page feature

column2: As several of you have pointed out, there's a major problem with the calendar not recording this last week's exercises. I'm working on the issue and I'll keep you updated.

Hi everyone. Well, I've tracked down the bug that's keeping questions from being recorded. I'm fixing it today, but I'm working directly on the live version of the site (to avoid complications when I upload new updated files). This means you may get some strange errors if you're trying to do a question while I'm working on a file. Sorry about this, but it's the fastest way for me to get the problem fixed. Thanks for your understanding.

Alright I've succeeded in breaking the site. It will seem to work, but it will evaluate any answer 'correct' and won't record your responses. >sigh< I'll keep working on it today and let you know here when it's back in functional order.

Alright, the site is back up and should be working better than ever. Sorry for the extended down time. It turned out to be a tough nut to crack. But your question attempts should all be tracked accurately now and the time zone should be treated properly. Your profile pages are not very pretty at the moment, and you'll need to scroll down past 10 empty months to see your November calendar, but the information is all there. Happy learning.

Hi folks. I'm back from San Francisco, mostly recovered from jet-lag, and making some more improvements. I've found and fixed another bug in the calendar records, so your questions should now be appearing on the right day. I also added a tabbed menu to your profile pages to make them easier to navigate.
column3: Another calendar fix and tabs for your profiles

column3:
# Why Learn Greek?
- the language of scripture
-- we want to hear God's voice as clearly as we can
- translations are not inspired
-- every English translation is an interpretation
-- good enough for many purposes
-- but God's voice is "muffled"

# Can I Really Learn Greek?
- yes you can!
-- you're not too old
-- you're not too bad at languages
-- you don't need a great memory
-- anyone can learn it
- what does it take?  
-- be consistent   
-- be patient  
-- be realistic

# A Familiar Cousin
- Most of us find the Greek alphabet intimidating at first
- But there are a lot of familiar letters
-- The Greek alphabet was the source of our own

# Alpha
----------
|α Α|
======
|"ball"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks just like our letter "a"
- never a short "a" like "hat"
- always a long a like "mall" or "ball"

# Beta

[[bird[bird] http://127.0.0.1:8000/paideia/static/images/bird.png right 200px]]

----------
|β Β|
======
|"bird"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our capital "B" with a short tail
- sounds just like our "b" as in "bird"
-- later Greeks came to pronounce it like "v"

# Delta

--------
|δ Δ|
====
|"dipper" / "dart"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- lower case looks like our "d" tilted forward
- upper case is a triangle
-- can sometimes be confused with "A"
- sounds like our "d" as in "dipper" or "dart"

# Epsilon

--------
|ε Ε|
====
|"edge"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our "e"
- sounds like our short "e" as in "edge"
-- never long "e" like "mere"
-- never "ay" sound like "werewolf"
-- never silent, even at the end of a word

# Iota

--------
|ι Ι|
======
|"ski"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks just like our "i"
-- no dot over the lower-case ι
- usually sounds like "ee" as in "ski"
-- occasionally a shorter "i" as in "pin"
-- never a long "eye" as in "mile"

# Kappa

--------
|κ Κ|
======
|"kite"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks just like our upper case "K"
-- lower-case looks like a shrunken "K"
- sounds like our "k" as in "kite"

# Mu

--------
|μ Μ|
======
|"mole"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- lower case looks like very rounded "m" with long arm
-- careful not to confuse with our "u"
- sounds like our "m" as in "mole"

# Omicron

--------
|ο Ο|
======
|"ostrich"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our "o"
- always sounds like our short "o" as in "ostrich"
-- never a long "o" like in "hole"
-- Greek has another letter for the long-"o" sound
- "omicron" literally means "little o"

# Sigma (final)

--------
|ς|
======
|"snake"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- this is how sigma looks at the *end* of a word
-- looks different in the middle of a word
-- a hold-over from the practices of medieval scribes
- looks like our "s" except that it curves below the line
-- the upper curve is often larger than the lower curve
- always sounds like our "s" as in "snake"
-- never like "z" as in "has"

# Tau

----------
|τ Τ|
======
|"table"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our capital "T"
-- lower case looks like a shrunken "T"
- sounds just like our "t" as in "table"

# Upsilon

----------
|υ Υ|
======
|"eeeew!"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our "u"
-- upper case looks like our "Y"
-- both our "u" and "y" come from upsilon
- sound is between "oo" and "ee"
-- like German *ü*
-- a bit like the exclamation "eeeew!" 
-- many just pronounce like "u" in "rude"

# Rough Breathing Mark

----------
|ἁ|
======
|"heart"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- Greek has no letter 'h'
-- the ones that look like 'h' actually make a very different sound
- The 'h' sound is made by a mark above the letter
-- almost always at the beginning of a word
-- only over a vowel *or* the letter ρ

column2: Alphabet II - Greek Letters in Modern Life
column3:
# Greek Letters in Modern Life

- There are quite a few other Greek letters that don't look like any English letters
- But several of these may be familiar from their use in math and science

# Pi

----------
|π Π|
======
|"path"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used in math for the number 3.1415 (etc.) that lets us calculate the measurements of a circle
- looks a bit like a path leading to the horizon
-- upper is just taller and more square
- sound is just like the English "p"
-- always a hard "p"
-- never a soft "ph", even beside other letters
-- letter name pronounced like "pea" not "pie"

# Gamma
----------
|γ Γ|
======
|"grass"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used for many things in the sciences
-- including "gamma" radiation
- looks a bit like two blades of grass
-- growing up from a root under the ground
- sounds like a hard "g" as in "grass"
-- never a soft "g" as in "gem"

# Double Gamma

----------
|γγ|
======
|"spring"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- when two gammas appear together their sound changes
- sounds like "ng" in "spring"
-- not like "ng" in "angel"
- looks a bit like more blades of grass growing
-- so it must be spring!

# Gamma-Kappa Combination

----------
|γκ|
======
|"ankle"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- when γ appears with κ its sound changes again
-- pretty hard to pronounce a hard "g" and "k" together!
- sounds like "nk" in "ankle"
-- an "ng" sound followed by "k"

# Theta

----------
|θ Θ|
======
|"thumb"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used for several things in math and science
-- "theta waves" are one frequency of brain activity
- lower case looks a bit like a thumb 
-- cross-bar marks the thumb nail
-- upper case is more round, with a "floating" crossbar
- sounds like "th" in "thumb"
-- never "th" as in "the" or "though"
-- always "voiceless," never "voiced"

# Lambda

----------
|λ Λ|
======
|"lobster"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used for several things in math and science
-- the half-life of radioactive materials (hence in the video game "Half-Life")
-- a wavelength in physics
-- an "anonymous function" in programming
- lower case looks a bit like a lobster
-- two claws reaching down, tail at the top
-- upper case a simple upside-down "V" (don't confuse it with Α or Δ!)
- sounds like english "l"

# Psi

----------
|ψ Ψ|
======
|"upside down"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- often used as a symbol for psychology
-- because the Greek word "psyche" starts with it: ψυχη.
- looks a bit like an upside-down umbrella
-- curved umbrella with handle sticking up
- sounds like "ps" in "upside" or "oops"
-- the "p" sound is not silent (*not* like English "psychology")
-- a bit tricky at first since we don't start words with that sound combination

# Omega

----------
|ω Ω|
======
|"ocean"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- familiar from theology (Jesus the alpha and omega)
-- in electricity represents an "ohm" (unit of resistance)
- looks a bit like a boat hull floating on the ocean
- sounds like the long "o" in "ocean"
-- never a short "o" as in "log"

# English Words with Greek Letters

- Now we can spell even more English words
-- remember that you're making the English *sounds* with Greek letters
-- not finding Greek "equivalents" for each letter
----------
thing|θιγγ
call|καλ
leapt|λεπτ
pet|πετ
-----------:letter_table[word_list]

column2: Greek Words II - Greek Words in English
column3:
# Recognizing Greek Words in English
- We often find multiple Greek words stuck together in one English term
- theology (theo + log + y)
-- θεος = "God" or "a god"
-- λογος = "word" or "reasoning"
-- so "speaking or reasoning about God"
- often Greek is used for English prefixes
-- megachurch 
-- μεγας = "big, large"

# Smooth Breathing Mark

----------
|ὀ|
======
|"open"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- another mark signals the "absence" of the "h" sound
-- seems a bit odd to us
- just indicates an ordinary vowel-sound
-- as in "open" or "ambulance"
-- in fact, there is a slight burst of air from the throat (in English as well as Greek)
- keep the two breathing marks straight!
-- open at the front, sounds like "open"

column2: Noun Basics - What Is A Noun?
column3:
What Is A Noun?
- Something we may have learned in elementary school
-- but are afraid to admit we've forgotten!
- "a person, place or thing"
-- but "thing" has to be taken broadly

# Examples of English Nouns

- house, keyboard, coffee
- fire, thought, rule
- woman, fire-fighter
- city, galaxy, corner

# Proper nouns vs. common nouns

- most nouns are "common" nouns        
- "proper nouns" name a specific object in the world
-- Mary (vs. woman)
-- Toronto (vs. city)
-- earth vs. planet
- proper nouns often capitalized in English
-- we do the same in Greek 
-- but this is anachronistic (no lower-case letters!)

# Using Our ΑΒΓ's

- We can use these Greek letters to spell out familiar English words
-- pay attention to the sounds of the word, not the English letters
-- look for Greek letters that make those sounds
-------------
bed|βεδ
deck|δεκ
deal|διλ
mute|μυτ
-------------
- To begin with the townspeople will ask you to do the same thing to help you become comfortable with the Greek letters and their sounds

column2: Greek Words I - Sounding Out Greek
column3:
# Your First Greek Words

- Now that you've learned the alphabet, you can already sound out many Greek words
-- τυπος
-- τομος

# Greek Is Everywhere In English
- Many English words are actually Greek transliterated
- watch for common patterns
-- υ becomes "y" in English (not "u")
-- often the Greek word ending dropped off
--- τυπος becomes "type"
-- endings often replaced
--- -ια becomes "-y" in English
- Most medical terms are Greek
-- τομος = "a cut"
-- τομια = "cutting"
--- so lobo-tomy (cutting the lobes)
-- διχος = "double, in two"
--- so dicho-tomy (cutting in two)

column2: Greek Words I - First Words to Know
column3:
# A Few Words You Will Use

- Answering "yes" or "no"
----------
ναι|yes
οὐ/οὐκ |no
----------
- Feedback from the townspeople
----------
καλον|good, well done
κακον|bad, poorly done
οὐ κακον|not bad!
----------

# A Few More Useful Words

- Here are some more useful words that you should review for a moment. 
-- You don't have to memorize them yet, since you'll be learning them as you talk with the townspeople
--------------
καί|and
τε|and
δε|and (or "but")
--------------

column2: Case Basics - What Is a Case?
column3:
# What Is a Noun's "Case"?

- Not a familiar idea for English speakers
- "case" in the sense of a job, an assignment
-- the word is "on the case"
- case = a job for a noun to do in a clause
-- how does it modify the other words?
-- how does it contribute the the overall idea of the clause?
- nouns take different forms in different "cases"
-- like uniforms for different jobs
--- different endings (usually)
--- different stems (sometimes)

# Noun Cases in English?

- English does have cases (nouns play different roles)
-- subject, possessive, direct object, indirect object, etc.
- English no longer uses different word-forms to indicate a noun's case
-- "The *ball* flew."
-- "She caught the *ball*."
-- "He gave credit to the *ball*."
-- case "uniforms" only survive in English personal pronouns
----------------
I|he|she|us
my|his|her|our|our
to me|to him|to her|to us
me|him|her|us
----------------
- Why don't we use word forms to indicate a noun's role?
-- replaced by word order & prepositions

column2: Case Basics - So Why Case Forms?
column3:
# Why Does Greek Use Different Case Forms?

- English can use word order to show a word's job
-- "The girl fed the dog."
-- "The dog fed the girl."
--- two very different ideas!
- In Greek, word order doesn't tell us much
-- You can rearrange the words without changing the idea
--- θεος ἠν ὁ λογος
--- ὁ λογος ἠν θεος
-- So you need different endings to know whether a noun is the subject, object, etc.

# The "Nominative" Case

- you might already recognize this case
-- it's used as the "dictionary form" of a noun
--- λογος
--- θεος
--- τομος
- how do we recognize a word's *nominative* form?
-- endings
--- three different patterns of noun endings
--- we call these "declensions"
-- stem change
--- only one declension (pattern) changes more than just the ending

# Nominative Case Endings

--------------
|masculine|
||
|feminine|
||
|neuter|
--------------:nominative_bg_table

--------------
2|-ος|||
1|-η or -α||-ις, -υς, etc.|3
2|-ο or -ον|||
--------------:nominative_fg_table

# Examples of Nominative Case Nouns

--------------
|masculine|
||
|feminine|
||
|neuter|
--------------:nominative_bg_table

--------------
2|λόγος, θέος|||
1|γυνή, παιδίσκη||παῖς, ἰχθυς, μητηρ|3
2|τέκνον, παιδίον|||
--------------:nominative_fg_table

# Some Implications For . . .

- the way we read English translations
-- it's important to realize what we ''can't'' tell from a translation
-- the word order is often very different in Greek
--- sometimes that flexible word order used for emphasis
- John 1:1
--------
θέος ἤν ὁ λόγος | "The word was God."
--------
-- "God" (θεος) is the ''first'' word in the Greek clause
-- stressing that the word was ''God'' (and not anything less!)

# Gender Confusion?

- in many languages, words have "gender"
-- a chair might be "he"
-- the sun might be "she"
- unfamiliar to many English speakers
-- usually only people and animals are "he" or "she"
-- everything else is "it" (neuter)

# Gender in French

- only a few remnants in English
-- calling a ship "she"
--- though maybe more due to personification
- if you've taken some French, this will be more familiar
-- **le** chat (always **il**)
-- **la** bibliotheque (always **elle**)

# Grammatical Gender vs. Real Gender

- There is usually no connection!
-- in French **every** cat is **le** chat (masc.) 
--- even though some are male and some female
-- every flower is **la** fleur (fem.)
-- every library is **la** bibliotheque (fem.)
--- but inanimate objects aren't really thought to be male or female
- words for human beings sometimes fit real gender
-- **la** femme (fem.), **l**'homme (masc.)
- but other times the grammatical gender still doesn't fit real gender
-- l'humain (human being), masc.
-- les gens (masc. pl.)
-- in German **das Kind** (child) is neuter! 
--- but they don't think children are genderless

# Grammatical Gender in Greek
- three genders
-- masculine
-- feminine
-- neuter
--- like German and Latin
- think of it as simply a grammatical category
-- will help us later on to line words up with their adjectives, etc.
